{
  "intro": {
    "title": "Word Formation (Part 3)",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Word Formation — build the word that fits",
        "content": "In FCE and CAE, Word Formation is **Part 3**: a text with **eight gaps**, and at the end of each line a stem word in **CAPITALS**. You form a new word from the stem to fit the gap.\n- The same stem gives different words: **HOPE** → *hopeful*, *hopefully*, *hopeless* — the sentence decides.\n- The task tests **prefixes**, **suffixes**, and **word families** (noun, verb, adjective, adverb).",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "text": "Read the whole sentence first. The meaning tells you whether you need a noun, adjective, adverb — or a negative form."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B1.word_formation.basic"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B1"
      },
      {
        "title": "Common suffixes — changing word class",
        "content": "Suffixes turn one word class into another. These patterns cover most exam answers:",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "headers": [
              "Suffix",
              "Makes",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**-tion / -sion / -ment**",
                "noun",
                "decide → decision; develop → development"
              ],
              [
                "**-ence / -ance**",
                "noun",
                "different → difference; appear → appearance"
              ],
              [
                "**-ful / -less**",
                "adjective",
                "hope → hopeful; care → careless"
              ],
              [
                "**-ive / -able**",
                "adjective",
                "effect → effective; rely → reliable"
              ],
              [
                "**-ly**",
                "adverb",
                "quick → quickly; happy → happily"
              ]
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B1.word_formation.basic"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B1"
      },
      {
        "title": "Negative prefixes & spelling",
        "content": "Negative forms are made with prefixes — and the exam loves them:",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "groups": [
              {
                "label": "un-",
                "items": [
                  "able → unable",
                  "happy → unhappy"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "in-",
                "items": [
                  "correct → incorrect",
                  "formal → informal"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "im-",
                "items": [
                  "possible → impossible",
                  "patient → impatient"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "dis-",
                "items": [
                  "agree → disagree",
                  "honest → dishonest"
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "label": "Spelling",
            "text": "One wrong letter makes the whole answer wrong. Double-check the spelling of every word you form."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.word_formation.prefixes_suffixes"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      },
      {
        "title": "Method & reference",
        "content": "1. Read the **whole sentence** (and the sentences around it). Understand the meaning.\n2. Look at the **stem word** in capitals.\n3. Decide: noun? adjective? adverb? **negative**?\n4. Form the word and **check the spelling**.\n\nA reference list with the **30 most common prefixes and suffixes** lives in **Reference → Word Formation: Prefixes & Suffixes**.\n\n[[ref|Reference lists]]",
        "root_ids": [
          "B1.word_formation.basic"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B1"
      }
    ]
  },
  "check": {
    "title": "Check you understand",
    "questions": [
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "What do you do with the word in capitals?",
        "options": {
          "a": "Copy it into the gap",
          "b": "Make a new word from it that fits the gap",
          "c": "Ignore it",
          "d": "Use it in the next sentence"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "You make a new word (e.g. HOPE → hopeful) that fits the gap."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "How many gaps are there in Part 3?",
        "options": {
          "a": "Five",
          "b": "Six",
          "c": "Eight",
          "d": "Ten"
        },
        "correct_option": "c",
        "explanation": "There are usually eight gaps."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Which of these can you make from HAPPY?",
        "options": {
          "a": "happiness",
          "b": "happily",
          "c": "unhappy",
          "d": "All of these"
        },
        "correct_option": "d",
        "explanation": "Happy can make happiness (noun), happily (adverb), and unhappy (negative)."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Does spelling matter?",
        "options": {
          "a": "No",
          "b": "Yes, the word must be spelled correctly",
          "c": "Only for long words",
          "d": "Only in the first gap"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Spelling must be correct for the answer to be right."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "What should you do before you write your answer?",
        "options": {
          "a": "Only look at the stem word",
          "b": "Read the whole sentence to understand meaning and grammar",
          "c": "Guess straight away",
          "d": "Skip the gap"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Reading the sentence helps you choose the right form (noun, adjective, etc.) and meaning."
      }
    ]
  },
  "practice_order": [
    "guidance"
  ],
  "practice": {
    "guidance": {
      "title": "Guided Practice: Word Formation",
      "questions": [
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "The weather was _____ (SUN) so we went to the beach.",
          "options": {
            "a": "sunny",
            "b": "sun",
            "c": "sunned",
            "d": "sunshine"
          },
          "correct_option": "a",
          "explanation": "We need an adjective: sunny (describes the weather)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "She spoke very _____ (QUIET) so as not to wake the baby.",
          "options": {
            "a": "quiet",
            "b": "quietly",
            "c": "quietness",
            "d": "quieter"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Adverb: quietly (how she spoke)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "We need to make a _____ (DECIDE) by Friday.",
          "options": {
            "a": "decide",
            "b": "decided",
            "c": "decision",
            "d": "deciding"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Noun: decision (make a decision)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "The _____ (LOCAL) were very friendly.",
          "options": {
            "a": "locally",
            "b": "location",
            "c": "locals",
            "d": "locate"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Noun (plural): locals (people who live there)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "It was a _____ (WONDER) holiday.",
          "options": {
            "a": "wonderful",
            "b": "wondered",
            "c": "wonderfully",
            "d": "wondering"
          },
          "correct_option": "a",
          "explanation": "Adjective: wonderful (describes the holiday)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "He completed the task _____ (SUCCESS).",
          "options": {
            "a": "success",
            "b": "successful",
            "c": "successfully",
            "d": "succeed"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Adverb: successfully (how he completed it)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "There was a lot of _____ (ACTIVE) in the classroom.",
          "options": {
            "a": "active",
            "b": "action",
            "c": "activity",
            "d": "actively"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Noun: activity (a lot of activity)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "The results were _____ (DISAPPOINT).",
          "options": {
            "a": "disappoint",
            "b": "disappointed",
            "c": "disappointing",
            "d": "disappointment"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Adjective: disappointing (describes the results)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "She has great _____ (DETERMINE) to succeed.",
          "options": {
            "a": "determine",
            "b": "determined",
            "c": "determination",
            "d": "determining"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Noun: determination (has + noun)."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "The book is _____ (READ) in one sitting.",
          "options": {
            "a": "read",
            "b": "readable",
            "c": "reader",
            "d": "reading"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Adjective: readable (you can read it)."
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
